Recall that the definition of the derivative of a function \emph{f} at
\emph{x} is

\begin{align*}
f'(x) := \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{f(x+h) - f(x)}{h}
\end{align*}

Following hint 1, we see that if $\displaystyle x = 3$ and
$f(x) = \sqrt{x}$, then

\begin{align*}
f'(3) &= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{\sqrt{3+h} - \sqrt3}{h} = L \\
L &= {\color{blue} \frac{1}{2\sqrt{3}}}
\end{align*}
